<font color="#FF0000">LOST IN THE WOODS</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug  6  1:39:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
There is a lot to be said about Pavlovian conditioning.  Warfare conditions and imprints a lot of stuff.  We are hypervigilent.  There are intrusive thoughts.  We do react adversly to many uncatalogued stimuli.  At the subconscieous level we experience nightmares.  There is suppressed thought and repressed thought.  We have both and my deal with each differently.  Suppressed thought is when something traumatic happened to me and I just don't want to talk about it at this very moment.  I am aware of the problem.  I processed a portion of it, but I will deal with it later (sound familiar?)  Repressed thought is a different kind of bear.  It occurs when so much is going on that you don't have the ability to deal with it all.  Some things get into your head without the benefit of you putting a label or file number on it.  This stuff is like a loose cannon rolling on the deck.  It serves to frustrate you forever.  These are the emotions that you can't quite put a handle on.  In order to deal with repressed thoughts and feelings, you have to go back and open old wounds.  It is good to have someone who &quot;Understands&quot; to help you find the way.  It is a painful process.<br>
It is not good to look upon Vietnam as Hmunga, a dreaded mystery.  Our brothers are Cante Tinza, those with Brave Hearts.  Akicita Was'te, Good Warriors are not canoni, those who wander in the woods forever.  We must embrace life like Anpagliwin, a beautiful woman who returns at dawn.<br>
Remember that you are my friend, we will not respond to nagi<br>
napeyapi, psychic shock... nothing will make our spirits run away.
<p><code>-- eramon@edumaster  (Humming Eagle) </code><p>


